@node "DEVELOPE" "Developer Information"
@next "FENSTER"
@prev "PROGRAMMTEILE"

  Accessing TURD from the outside world is currently possible via two ways:

  1) The spooler message port.
     A C++ header file called "TURD_II_Export.h" is needed to use this port from
     your application. This file is available from the @{"author" link "AUTOR" 0}.
     This message port is directly connected to the spooler process and accepts
     simple 1-byte data which is forwarded to the @{"port window" link "NID_PortWindow" 0}.
     Since the port is part of the spooler process he's running asyncronously and
     with a higher priority than the rest of TURD.
     
  2) The ARexx port.
     This port is way slower than the spooler message port and, apart from that,
     is not running asyncronously. On the other hand he is easier to use because
     of ARexx. This interface supports several @{"comands" link "AREXX" 0} that may also control the user
     interface and is availabe as command host as well as function host.
     For more information about ARexx please consult your Amiga ARexx User Guide
     or similiar books. Additionally two small @{"ARexx demos" link "AREXX-EXAMPLES" 0} are available which may
     be used to test the port.

     The Arexx port is available for registered user only.

  The names of these ports are displayed in the information requester which you
  can open using the menu or gadget @{"Main Window / Program / About" link "NID_MainAbout" 0}.
  
@endnode

@node "AREXX" "Index Of The Supported ARexx-Commands"

  @{u}The standard return codes (RC) are:@{uu}
  
  0   RC_OK      No errors. Returned by all functions on successful completion.
  
  5   RC_WARN    TURD was not able to process the command completely. The cause
                 depends on the function. Not returned by all functions.
                 
  10  RC_ERROR   Processing of the command was stopped due to an error. May also
                 be returned if the given command is unknown or a wrong argument
                 list was supplied. Returned by all functions.
  
  20  RC_FATAL   Fatal error. Returned if the port is not able to accept a command,
                 e.g. if TURD is currently closed down.

  No function will return a secondary result (using RESULT) at the moment.


  @{u}T.U.R.D.II knows the following ARexx commands:@{uu}

  QUIT [REQUEST]
    Quits the program.
    
    REQUEST
      Open a requester that asks the user if s/he really wants to quit TURD.
  
    Result: RC

    
  ICONIFY
    Iconify the program.
    All windows will be closed and an icon appears on the Workbench. If the
    program is already iconified this command is ignored.

    Result: RC


  UNICONIFY
    The user interface is re-opened.
    If the program is currently not iconified this command is ignored.

    Result: RC


  CLOSEPORT
    Close the ARexx port.
    Be careful: after this command has been executed the port cannot be
    opened again!

    Result: RC


  OPENLISTWIN
    Open the list window.

    Result: RC

    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.
    RC_ERROR is returned if the window could not be opened.


  OPENSCHEWIN
    Open the schedule window.

    Result: RC

    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.
    RC_ERROR is returned if the window could not be opened.


  OPENRANDWIN
    Open the randomize window.

    Result: RC

    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.
    RC_ERROR is returned if the window could not be opened.


  OPENOUTWIN
    Open the output window.
    
    Result: RC

    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.
    RC_ERROR is returned if the window could not be opened.


  OPENMAINWIN
    Open the main window.

    Result: RC

    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.
    RC_ERROR is returned if the window could not be opened.


  OPENCONFIGWIN
    Open the configuration window.

    Result: RC

    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.
    RC_ERROR is returned if the window could not be opened.


  OPENMUSICWIN
    Open the music window.

    Result: RC

    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.
    RC_ERROR is returned if the window could not be opened.


  CLOSELISTWIN
    Close the list window.

    Result: RC
    
    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.


  CLOSESCHEWIN
    Close the schedule window.

    Result: RC

    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.


  CLOSERANDWIN
    Close the randomize window.

    Result: RC

    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.


  CLOSEOUTWIN
    Close the output window.

    Result: RC

    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.


  CLOSEMAINWIN
    Close the main window.

    Result: RC

    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.


  CLOSECONFIGWIN
    Close the configuration window.

    Result: RC

    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.


  CLOSEMUSICWIN
    Close the music window.

    Result: RC

    RC_WARN is returned if the program is iconified.


  LOADLIST <filename.list>
    Load the list file <filename.list>.
    The processing of a currently loaded list file is aborted!

    Result: RC


  LOADSCHEDULE <filename.time>
    Load the schedule file <filename.time>.
    The processing of a currently loaded schedule file is aborted!

    Result: RC


  SETMUSICSOURCE <HIPPOPLAYER | TT2DIGITIZER>
    Set a new source of music for use by the music window.
    The processing of another music source is stopped. The new music source
    will not be opened and a previously stopped processing of this source
    is not restarted! You will have to do this e.g. manually or with the
    command STARTMUSIC.

    HIPPOLPLAYER
      The new music source is the Hippo module player.
    
    TT2DIGITIZER
      The new music source is the Techno-Turbo-Sound II Digitizer connected
      to the internal parallel interface.

    Result: RC


  PUTOUTCHAR <char>
    The ASCII-code of <char> is send to the relais card.

    This command is meant for some specific uses only due to the fact that
    only visible characters which are legal ARexx tokens are allowed.

    Result: RC

    If a string is supplied only the first character of this string is
    send to the card and RC_WARN is returned

    RC_ERROR is returned if the character could not be send to the card due
    to a busy or unavailable spooler port.


  PUTOUTDEC <decimal>
    The value <decimal> is send to the relais card.
    
    Result: RC

    If this number is not between 0 and 255 TURD 'truncates' the value and
    returns RC_WARN.

    RC_ERROR is returned if the value could not be send to the card due
    to a busy or unavailable spooler port.


  PUTOUTHEX <hex>
    The value <hex> is send to the relais card.

    Result: RC

    If this number is not between 0 and FF TURD 'truncates' the value and
    returns RC_WARN.

    RC_ERROR is returned if the value could not be send to the card due
    to a busy or unavailable spooler port.

 
  PUTOUTBIN <binary>
    The value <binary> is send to the relais card.

    Result: RC
    
    If this number is not between 00000000 and 11111111 TURD 'truncates'
    the value and returns RC_WARN.

    RC_ERROR is returned if the value could not be send to the card due
    to a busy or unavailable spooler port.
 
 
  PUTOUTCLEAR
    Clear all bits of the output.
    This is similar to e.g. 'PUTOUTBIN 00000000'.

    Result: RC

    RC_ERROR is returned if the bits could not be cleared due to a busy
    or unavailable spooler port.
 
 
  STARTRAND
    Start the output of values from the randomize window.

    Result: RC
 
 
  STARTLIST
    Start the processing of the loaded list file by the list window.

    Result: RC

    RC_ERROR is returned and the processing is aborted if the list contains
    errors (especially illegal labels).

 
  STARTSCHEDULE
    Start the processing of the loaded schedule file by the schedule window.

    Result: RC
 
 
  STARTMUSIC
    Start the processing of the selected music source by the music window.

    Result: RC
 
 
  STOPRAND
    Stop the output of values from the randomize window.

    Result: RC
 

  STOPLIST
    Stop the processing of the loaded list file by the list window.

    Result: RC
 
 
  STOPSCHEDULE
    Stop the processing of the loaded schedule file by the schedule window.

    Result: RC
 
 
  STOPMUSIC
    Stop the processing of the selected music source by the music window and
    close the music source.

    Result: RC
 
 
  Of course new commands will be added from time to time.

@endnode

@node "AREXX-EXAMPLES" "How To Use ARexx"

  @{u}Example for the use of the command host:@{uu}

  /* Command server test */
  address 'TURD_Arexx_Port_0'
  'PUTOUTBIN 00110011'


  @{u}Example for the use of the function host:@{uu}

  /* Function server test */
  ADDLIB('TURD_Arexx_Port_0',0)
  Say PUTOUTBIN('01100110')


  Both examples have to be written to a file (e.g. "test.rexx") and then
  started from the Shell using "rx test.rexx".


  You can also execute single ARexx commands without writing a new script
  using the following Shell command:

  rx "address 'TURD_Arexx_Port_0' PUTOUTBIN 11001100"

@endnode

@node "FENSTER" "The Program Windows"
@next "NID_MainWindow"
@prev "DEVELOPE"

  The application uses several windows, each covering specific functions. All can
  be closed by either pressing the close gadget or using the <Esc>-key and opened
  by the respective button in the @{"main window" link "NID_MainWindow" 0}.
  One exception is the @{"main window" link "NID_MainWindow" 0} itself. Closing this one means leaving T.U.R.D. II.

  The <Tab>-key activates the first text or numeric gadget of the active window.

  @{u}More information about these windows:@{uu}

  @{" Main Window           " link "NID_MainWindow" 0}
  @{" Port Window           " link "NID_PortWindow" 0}
  @{" Random Window         " link "NID_RandomWindow" 0}
  @{" Schedule Window       " link "NID_TimeWindow" 0}
  @{" List Windows          " link "NID_ListWindow" 0}
  @{" Music Window          " link "NID_MusicWindow" 0}
  @{" Configuration Window  " link "NID_ConfigWindow" 0}

  @{" Window Selection Requester " link "NID_WinSelectWindow" 0}
@endnode

@node "NID_MainWindow" "The Main Window"
@next "NID_PortWindow"
@prev "FENSTER"

  The main window is of course the most important one. It controls all other
  windows of the application.
  
  @{u}You can find the following gadgets and displays here:@{uu}

  @{fg highlight} Program  @{fg text}
  @{" About       " link "NID_MainAbout" 0}
  @{" Config      " link "NID_MainConfig" 0}
  @{" Iconify     " link "NID_MainIconify" 0}
  @{" Guide       " link "NID_MainGuide" 0}
  @{" Quit        " link "NID_MainQuit" 0}

  @{fg highlight} Windows   @{fg text}
  @{" Port        " link "NID_MainPort" 0}
  @{" Music       " link "NID_MainMusic" 0}
  @{" List        " link "NID_MainList" 0}
  @{" Schedule    " link "NID_MainTime" 0}
  @{" Random      " link "NID_MainRandom" 0}

  @{fg highlight} Clock       @{fg text}
  @{" Time        " link "NID_MainTimeC" 0}
  @{" Date        " link "NID_MainDateC" 0}
  @{" Weekday     " link "NID_MainWeekdayC" 0}

  If a window is already open you can activate and push it to the front by
  pressing the respective gadget.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainAbout" "Main Window / Program / About"

  This gadget opens an info requester that contains some short informations
  about the application and if it's @{"registered" link "REGISTER" 0} or not and the names
  of the public massage port and the Arexx port.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainConfig" "Main Window / Program / Config"

  This gadget opens the @{"config window" link "NID_ConfigWindow" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainIconify" "Main Window/ Program / Iconify"

  This gadget closes all windows and the screen - the program goes into
  stand-by mode but it will keep on running and process its data.
  You can reopen the user interface by double-clicking on the icon that
  appears on the Workbench.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainGuide" "Main Window / Program / Guide"

  Opens the @{"contents page" link "MAIN" 0} of this guide.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainQuit" "Main Window / Program / Quit"

  You can leave T.U.R.D. II by pressing this gadget. A requester will pop up and
  ask if you really want to leave this fine application.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainMusic" "Main Window / Windows / Music"

  This gadget opens the @{"music window" link "NID_MusicWindow" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainList" "Main Window / Windows / List"

  This gadget opens the @{"list window" link "NID_ListWindow" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainTime" "Main Window / Windows / Schedule"

  This gadget opens the @{"Schedule Window /" link "NID_TimeWindow" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainRandom" "Main Window / Windows / Random"

  This gadget opens the @{"random window" link "NID_RandomWindow" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainPort" "Main Window / Windows / Port"

  This gadget opens the @{"port window" link "NID_PortWindow" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainTimeC" "Main Window / Clock / Time"

  You can see the current time here.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainDateC" "Main Window / Clock / Date"

  You can see the current date here.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainWeekdayC" "Main Window / Clock / Weekday"

  You can see the current weekday here.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortWindow" "The Port Window"
@next "NID_RandomWindow"
@prev "NID_MainWindow"

  The port window controls any data that it send to the @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0}.
  All windows that generate data send them to the port window which in turn sends
  it to the @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0}. Of course you may modify the bits by hand, too.

  In addition to the standard menu shortcuts you can use the keys F1 to F8 to
  toggle the @{"port LEDs" link "NID_PortPort0" 0}.

  @{u}The port window contains the following gadgets and displays:@{uu}
  
  @{fg highlight}Port      Mask      Model      Outputs          Model@{fg text}
  @{"   0   " link "NID_PortPort0" 0}  @{" bit 0 " link "NID_PortMask0" 0}  @{"   0   " link "NID_PortModel0" 0}   @{" Enable       " link "NID_PortOutEnable" 0}  @{" Send          " link "NID_PortModelSend" 0}
  @{"   1   " link "NID_PortPort0" 0}  @{" bit 1 " link "NID_PortMask0" 0}  @{"   1   " link "NID_PortModel0" 0}   @{" Flip         " link "NID_PortOutFlip" 0}  @{" Invert        " link "NID_PortModelInvert" 0}
  @{"   2   " link "NID_PortPort0" 0}  @{" bit 2 " link "NID_PortMask0" 0}  @{"   2   " link "NID_PortModel0" 0}   @{" Invert       " link "NID_PortOutInvert" 0}  @{" Flip          " link "NID_PortModelFlip" 0}
  @{"   3   " link "NID_PortPort0" 0}  @{" bit 3 " link "NID_PortMask0" 0}  @{"   3   " link "NID_PortModel0" 0}   @{" Mask         " link "NID_PortOutMask" 0}  @{" Set all       " link "NID_PortModelSetAll" 0}
  @{"   4   " link "NID_PortPort0" 0}  @{" bit 4 " link "NID_PortMask0" 0}  @{"   4   " link "NID_PortModel0" 0}   @{" Refr. Value  " link "NID_PortRefValues" 0}  @{" Clear all     " link "NID_PortModelClear" 0}
  @{"   5   " link "NID_PortPort0" 0}  @{" bit 5 " link "NID_PortMask0" 0}  @{"   5   " link "NID_PortModel0" 0}   @{" Refr. Port   " link "NID_PortRefPort" 0}  @{"  <<   " link "NID_PortModelLeft" 0}@{"   >>  " link "NID_PortModelRight" 0}
  @{"   6   " link "NID_PortPort0" 0}  @{" bit 6 " link "NID_PortMask0" 0}  @{"   6   " link "NID_PortModel0" 0}
  @{"   7   " link "NID_PortPort0" 0}  @{" bit 7 " link "NID_PortMask0" 0}  @{"   7   " link "NID_PortModel0" 0}

  @{fg highlight}Port Value     Model Value    Miscellaneous@{fg text}
  @{"    Bin    " link "NID_PortPortBin" 0}   @{"    Bin    " link "NID_PortModelBin" 0}   @{" Output                        " link "NID_PortOutput" 0}@{" ? " link "NID_PortOutputSel" 0}
  @{"    Dez    " link "NID_PortPortDec" 0}   @{"    Dez    " link "NID_PortModelDec" 0}   @{" Output Device Unit            " link "NID_PortDevUnit" 0}
  @{"    Hex    " link "NID_PortPortHex" 0}   @{"    Hex    " link "NID_PortModelHex" 0}   @{" AMIGA CIA direct mode         " link "NID_PortCIAMode" 0}
@endnode

@node "NID_PortPort0" "Port Window / Port / 0-7"

  The eight port-LEDs show the current status of @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0} bits.
  A lit LED means that the respective port bit is on.
  You can modify the bits by hand by pressing one of the LED gadgets.

  All data that is output from a window or from the @{"model gadgets" link "NID_PortModel0" 0} will
  first be modified according to the output options, then filtered using
  the @{"port mask" link "NID_PortMask0" 0} and finally send to the @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0} and displayed in
  the port LEDs.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortMask0" "Port Window / Mask / 0-7"

  The mask gadgets are used to lock single @{"port LEDs" link "NID_PortPort0" 0}.
  A disabled (not checked) the mask gadget locks the respective port
  LED and thus prevents it from any further modifications.

  The mask function itself can be enabled or disabled using the
  @{"Mask" link "NID_PortOutMask" 0} button.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortModel0" "Port Window / Model / 0-7"

  These LEDs have some special function. They are basically working like the
  @{"port LEDs" link "NID_PortPort0" 0}, allowing you to manually control the @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0}, however they
  won't be modified by the other windows.
  There are also some buttons to e.g. move or set all bits.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortOutEnable" "Port Window / Output / Enable"

  If this button is disabled (not checked) no data will be send to
  the @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0}, however the generated data is still displayed
  by the @{"port LEDs" link "NID_PortPort0" 0}.

  @{u}Be careful:@{uu} If this button is not checked the data displayed by the
              LEDs will not be the same as the data output by the
              @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0}!

  If T.U.R.D. II wasn't able to open the @{"output device" link "NID_PortOutput" 0} it will
  automatically disable this button.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortOutInvert" "Port Window / Output / Invert"

  If enabled all data will be inverted prior to sending it to the @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0}.
  This affects all data from any window and your manual modifications.
  The @{"port LEDs" link "NID_PortPort0" 0} will continue to display the data like it is
  send to the @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortOutFlip" "Port Window / Output / Flip"

  If enabled all bits will be exchanged this way:
       bit 0 - bit 7
       bit 1 - bit 6
       bit 2 - bit 5
       bit 3 - bit 4

  This affects all data from any window and your manual modifications.
  The @{"port LEDs" link "NID_PortPort0" 0} will continue to display the data like it is
  send to the @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_PortOutMask" "Port Window / Output / Mask"

  This gadget activates the @{"port mask" link "NID_PortMask0" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortModelSend" "Port Window / Model / Send"

  If you press this button the data displayed by the @{"model LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0} will be send
  to the @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0}. Obviously this only makes sense if the
  data of the @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0} is not the same as the data displayed
  by the @{"modell LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0}, maybe if some other window send
  some data in the mean time.

@endnode

@node "NID_PortModelSetAll" "Port Window / Model / Set All"

  This gadget sets all @{"model LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortModelClear" "Port Window / Model / Clear All"

  This gadget clears all @{"model LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortModelInvert" "Port Window / Model / Invert"

  This gadget inverts the data displayed by the @{"model LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortModelFlip" "Port Window / Model / Flip"

  This gadget mirrors the bits in the @{"model LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0}.
  See also @{"Output/Flip" link "NID_PortOutFlip" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortModelLeft" "Port Window / Model / <<"

  Moves the bitmask displayed by the @{"model LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0} one step left, i.e.
  towards the most significant bit, #7.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortModelRight" "Port Window / Model / >>"

  Moves the bitmask displayed by the @{"model LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0} one step right, i.e.
  towards the least significant bit, #1.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortModelBin" "Port Window / Model Value / Bin"

  Displays the bitmask of the @{"model LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0} as binary number.
  You may also enter a number that is then displayed by the @{"model LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortModelDec" "Port Window / Model Value / Dec"

  Displays the bitmask of the @{"model LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0} as decimal number.
  You may also enter a number that is then displayed by the @{"model LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortModelHex" "Port Window / Model Value / Hex"

  Displays the bitmask of the @{"model LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0} as hex number.
  You may also enter a number that is then displayed by the @{"model LEDs" link "NID_PortModel0" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortPortBin" "Port Window / Port Value / Bin"

  Displays the current status of the @{"port LEDs" link "NID_PortPort0" 0} as binary number.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortPortDec" "Port Window / PortValue / Dec"

  Displays the current status of the @{"port LEDs" link "NID_PortPort0" 0} as decimal number.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortPortHex" "Port Window / PortValue / Hex"

  Displays the current status of the @{"port LEDs" link "NID_PortPort0" 0} as hex number.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortOutput" "Port Window / Miscellaneous / Output"

  This is the device that is used to output the data to the @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0}.
  Use "parallel.device" and unit 0 for the parallel Amiga printer port.
  This is also the default setting.

  @{b} The device name is case sensitive and thereforemust be in small case.@{ub}
@endnode

@node "NID_PortOutputSel" "Port Window / Miscellaneous / ?"

  Opens a file requester that shows the available devices.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortCIAMode" "Port Window / Miscellaneous / AMIGA CIA direct mode"

  This gadget enables the 'AMIGA CIA direct mode'. This way T.U.R.D. II directly writes
  to the hardware address of the internal parallel port instead of using a device.

  In this mode you can use @{"relay cards" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0} that do not use
  any Centronics protocol and/or @{"relay cards" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0} with relays
  that are directly connected to the eight data lines of the parallel port.

  This gadget has to be disabled for the better @{"relay cards" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0} that use a protocol.
  These may also be used on other parallel ports that the internal one.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortRefValues" "Port Window / Outputs / Refresh Values"

  This button enables the refresh of the port value displayes.
  If disabled these values won't correspond to the real status of the @{"port LEDs" link "NID_PortPort0" 0}.
  This saves some time if you are generating signals of high frequency,
  e.g. with the @{"music window" link "NID_MusicWindow" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortRefPort" "Port Window / Outputs / Refresh Port"

  This button enables the refresh of the @{"port LEDs" link "NID_PortPort0" 0}.
  If disabled the status displayed by the @{"port LEDs" link "NID_PortPort0" 0} won't correspond
  to the status of the data lines of your @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0}.
  This saves some time if you are generating signals of high frequency,
  e.g. with the @{"music window" link "NID_MusicWindow" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_PortDevUnit" "Port Window / Miscellaneous / Output Device Unit"

  This is the unit of the device that T.U.R.D. II uses for its output.
@endnode

@node "NID_RandomWindow" "The Random Window"
@next "NID_TimeWindow"
@prev "NID_PortWindow"

  The random window is used to send user specified random data to the
  relay card.

  @{u}The random window contains the following gadgets:@{uu}

  @{fg highlight}Miscellaneous@{fg text}
  @{" Bits to set " link "NID_RandomBitsToSet" 0}  @{" Frequency " link "NID_RandomFreqSlider" 0} @{"(Hz)" link "NID_RandomFreqNumber" 0}  @{" Process " link "NID_RandomProcess" 0}
@endnode

@node "NID_RandomBitsToSet" "Random Window / Miscellaneous / Bits To Set"

  This gadgets controls how many bits are set each turn. If you set it to e.g.
  "two", only two (randomly selected) bits will be set. "Random" produces a
  completely random bitmask (random amount of bits and random bit order).
@endnode

@node "NID_RandomFreqSlider" "Random Window / Miscellaneous / Frequency"

  This is the frequency (in Hertz, i.e. masks per second) at which new random
  bitmasks are produced.
@endnode

@node "NID_RandomFreqNumber" "Random Window / Miscellaneous / (Hz)"

  This gadget displays the currently selected frequency. You may enter values
  between 1 and 99 Hertz (bitmasks per second).
@endnode

@node "NID_RandomProcess" "Random Window / Miscellaneous / Process"

  If enabled the @{"random window" link "NID_RandomWindow" 0} will generate
  random bitmasks at the selected frequency and send them to the @{"output window" link "NID_PortWindow" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeWindow" "The Schedule Window"
@next "NID_ListWindow"
@prev "NID_RandomWindow"

  The schedule window provides functions to send data to the relay card on a
  specific time which may be specifed with an accurancy of a second. You can
  enable or disable each event separatly.
  In addition to send data directly to the output you may also start or stop
  actions of the other windows like the random window.

  If it's time to execute the event and if the Process checkbox and the event
  are enabled then the bit mask is send to the relay card, the window actions
  are taken as needed and the event is deactivated to prevent it from being
  executed again.

  @{u}You can find the following gadgets in the schedule window:@{uu}

  @{fg highlight}Schedule editor                  Schedule@{fg text}
  @{"                             " link "NID_TimeTable" 0}   @{" Save             " link "NID_TimeSave" 0}
  @{"                             " link "NID_TimeTable" 0}   @{" Save as          " link "NID_TimeSaveAs" 0}
  @{"                             " link "NID_TimeTable" 0}   @{" Load             " link "NID_TimeLoad" 0}
  @{"                             " link "NID_TimeTable" 0}   @{" Add file         " link "NID_TimeInsFile" 0}
  @{"                             " link "NID_TimeTable" 0}   @{" Print schedule   " link "NID_TimePrint" 0}
  @{"                             " link "NID_TimeTable" 0}   @{" Delete           " link "NID_TimeClear" 0}
  @{"   Add        " link "NID_TimeIns" 0} @{"   Clear     " link "NID_TimeDelete" 0}

  @{fg highlight}Schedule editor                 Miscellaneous@{fg text}
  @{"  Time    " link "NID_TimeTimeC" 0}@{" ? " link "NID_TimeTimeCR" 0}  @{"   Random    " link "NID_TimeRand" 0}   @{" Reports          " link "NID_TimeReports" 0}
  @{"  Date    " link "NID_TimeDateC" 0}@{" ? " link "NID_TimeDateCR" 0}  @{"   Music     " link "NID_TimeMusic" 0}   @{" Process          " link "NID_TimeProcess" 0}
  @{"  Pattern " link "NID_TimeData" 0}@{" ? " link "NID_TimeDataR" 0}  @{"   List      " link "NID_TimeList" 0}   

  @{" Delete afterwards " link "NID_TimeDelAfter" 0} @{" Active " link "NID_TimeActive" 0}
  @{" Title                       " link "NID_TimeTitle" 0}
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeTable" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Schedule"

  This list shows all currently known events sorted by time.
  Each entry starts with the first 12 characters of the title, followed by an @
  and the specific date and time for this event. Finally you will find the bit
  mask that will be send.
  You can edit the currently highlighted entry with the buttons from the date
  editor group.

  The list also accepts the following short cuts:

    <Return>      Add a new event.
    <Cursor up>   Activate the event above the currently active.
    <Cursor down> Activate the event below the currently active.
    <Del>         Delete the currently active event.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeIns" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Add"

  This buttons adds a new event to the schedule. The new event is initialized
  with the current date and time and deactivated.
  @{b}Note: If you want this event to be executed you will have to active it!@{ub}
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeDelete" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Delete"

  The currently highlighted event is removed from the list.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeTimeC" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Time"

  This is the time at which the currently selected event will be executed. The
  format is the one prefered in your country. If you don't know exactly which
  one this is just have a look at the clock in the main window.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeDateC" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Date"

  This is the date on which the currently selected event will be executed. The
  format is the one prefered in your country. If you don't know exactly which
  one this is just have a look at the clock in the main window.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeData" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Pattern"

  This is the bit mask that will be send if the event is executed.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeTimeCR" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Time_?"

  If you click on this button the event time will be set to the time
  received from the systems' clock.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeDateCR" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Date_?"

  If you click on this button the event date will be set to the time
  received from the systems' clock.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeDataR" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Pattern_?"

  The bit mask of the event will be set to the mask displayed in the
  model group in the output window.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeRand" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Random"

  Here you can start or stop (or do nothing at all) the generator of the
  random window if the event is executed.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeMusic" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Music"

  Here you can start or stop (or do nothing at all) the music of the
  random window if the event is executed.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeList" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / List"

  Here you can start or stop (or do nothing at all) list actions if
  the event is executed.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeDelAfter" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Delete afterwards"

  If this button is checked then the event will be deleted after has
  been executed.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeActive" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Active"

  This button enables or disables the selected event. Only enabled events
  will be executed.
  After execution an event is automatically disabled.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeTitle" "Schedule Window / Schedule Editor / Title"

  You can enter a name for the selected event with upto 40 characters. This
  is just for your information. The first characters of this title are also
  displayed in the @{"schedule" link "NID_TimeTable" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeReports" "Schedule Window / Miscellaneous / Reports"

  If this gadget is checked then the schedule window will open a requester
  after executing an event and wait for the users' response.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeProcess" "Schedule Window / Miscellaneous / Process"

  This gadget enables or disables the schedule window. If checked the schedule
  window will compare the current time with the time of each event every second
  and if one or more are the same, execute them.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeSave" "Schedule Window / Schedule / Save"

  The contents of the schedule is saved to last used file. If you did not
  load from or save to a file yet you will be asked for the path where the
  file should be saved.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeSaveAs" "Schedule Window / Schedule / Save as"

  A file requester is opened and asks you for the name of the file to which
  the contents of the schedule should be saved. The names should always end
  with ".time". This is optional but makes it easier to separate them from
  other files.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeInsFile" "Schedule Window / Schedule / Add file"

  A file requester is opened and asks you for the name of a schedule file.
  All events of this file are added to the current schedule.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeLoad" "Schedule Window / Schedule / Load"

  A file requester is opened and asks you for the name of a schedule file.
  All events of the current schedule are @{b}removed@{ub} and the events
  of this file are added to the schedule.

@endnode

@node "NID_TimePrint" "Schedule Window / Schedule / Print"

  The current @{"schedule" link "NID_TimeTable" 0} is written to the printer.
@endnode

@node "NID_TimeClear" "Schedule Window / Schedule / Delete"

  The current schedule is deleted.
  
  @{u}Be carefull:@{uu} All events will be lost!
@endnode

@node "NID_ListWindow" "The List Window"
@next "NID_MusicWindow"
@prev "NID_TimeWindow"

  The list window is for the effect- and listcontrol of the relay card. Every
  item on the list contains a bit mask, a jump count, a quantity of cycles and,
  as seen in the time window, gadgets with influence to the other control
  windows. If the list process is started the program sends one item of the
  list after the other to the interface. It starts with the item selected
  by the user, the so called selected item. Running lights and other effects
  can be easily defined and played this way. If the process is stopped
  the last transmitted item is diplayed in the list. Read the descriptions
  of the other gadgets to learn about more functions.

  @{u}The list window contains these functions:@{uu}

  @{fg highlight}List editor             Listfile@{fg text}
  @{"                    " link "NID_ListList" 0}   @{" Save           " link "NID_ListSave" 0}
  @{"                    " link "NID_ListList" 0}   @{" Save as        " link "NID_ListSaveAs" 0}
  @{"                    " link "NID_ListList" 0}   @{" Load           " link "NID_ListLoad" 0}
  @{"                    " link "NID_ListList" 0}   @{" Insert file    " link "NID_ListInsFile" 0}
  @{"                    " link "NID_ListList" 0}   @{" Print          " link "NID_ListPrint" 0}
  @{"                    " link "NID_ListList" 0}   @{" Clear          " link "NID_ListClear" 0}
  @{"                    " link "NID_ListList" 0}
  @{" Insert   " link "NID_ListIns" 0}@{" Delete  " link "NID_ListDelete" 0}

  @{fg highlight}Item editor             Miscelaneous@{fg text}
  @{" Pattern        " link "NID_ListData" 0}@{" ? " link "NID_ListDataRead" 0}   @{" Frequency  " link "NID_ListFreq" 0} @{"(Hz)" link "NID_ListFreqInt" 0}
  @{" Schedule           " link "NID_ListTime" 0}   @{" Process          " link "NID_ListProcess" 0}
  @{" Random             " link "NID_ListRand" 0}   
  @{" Music              " link "NID_ListMusic" 0}
  @{" Cycles             " link "NID_ListCycles" 0}
  @{" Jump               " link "NID_ListJump" 0}
@endnode

@node "NID_ListList" "List Window / List Editor / Effect List"

  This is the effect list. Every item on the list is represented by a
  number followed by it`s bit mask. A special item is the one named "END".
  It is always the last item and represents the final tag. Once the process
  reaches this item the list window stops processing. The item selected
  by the user will be called the selected item on the following pages.

  The list window accepts these shortcuts:
    <Return>      Insert new item.
    <Cursor up>   Select item above the highlighted item.
    <Cursor down> Select item below the highlisted item.
    <Del>         Delete selected item.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListIns" "List Window / List Editor / Insert"

  A new item is inserted above the currently selected.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListDelete" "List Window / List Editor / Delete"

  Delete the selected item.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListData" "List Window / Item Editor / Pattern"

  The bit mask to be send if the selected item is executed.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListDataRead" "List Window / Item Editor / Pattern_?"

  Read the bit mask from the current model of the port window.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListTime" "List Window / Item Editor / Schedule"

  Select the action to be done on the @{"Schedule Window /" link "NID_TimeWindow" 0} when the selected
  item will be processed.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListRand" "List Window / Item editor / Random"

  Select the action to be done on the @{"Random window" link "NID_RandomWindow" 0} when the selected
  item will be processed.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListMusic" "List Window / Item editor / Music"

  Select the action to be done on the @{"Music window" link "NID_MusicWindow" 0} when the selected
  item will be processed.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListCycles" "List Window / Item editor / Cycles"

  Use this gadget to select the amount of time the program is forced to wait
  after processing the selected item before it can process the next one. This
  period is indicated in cycles. The duration of one cycle depends on the
  selected processing frequency. If a frequency of 50Hz is selected and an
  item has two cycles, for example, this would result in a break of 2*1/50
  Seconds (0.04s) between this item and the next. Effects not linear in
  time can be easily realised using these functions.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListJump" "List Window / Item editor / Jump"

  Enter the item number to jump to after processing the selected item. This
  can be used to realise processes not put in a linear order.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListFreq" "List Window / Miscellaneous / Frequency"

  Select the processing frequency of the list window
@endnode

@node "NID_ListFreqInt" "List Window / Miscellaneous / (Hz)"

  Enter the processing frequency via keyboard. Valid values reach from 1 to 99 Hz.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListProcess" "List Window / Miscellaneous / Process"

  Use this gadget to start or stopt the list process. It starts at the selected
  item and stops when it reaches "END".

  Important:
  The program checks the list`s correctness at start if it`s changed or never
  has been processed before. If the program finds errors this way the user has
  to correct them manually and to restart the process. If a new check finds no
  errors anymore the list process is started. This state, `checked` or `not
  checked`, is also saved to your list file. Therefore the file`s content has
  not to be checked again if it`s not changed. This is of big importance if
  the list process is not started manually but automatically by another window.
  This automatic start is difficult if the list`s state is `not checked`.
  If the list process is started automatically and is not checked nevertheless,
  the program does this check and starts the list process as soon as possible,
  with delay.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListSave" "List Window / Effect List / Save"

  The list`s content is saved under the name of the last loaded list file. If no
  file has been loaded yet, a window opens where you can enter the file`s name.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListSaveAs" "List Window / Effect List / Save as"

  The list`s content is saved under your desired filename. A list file should always
  end with ".list" to tell it apart from other files easier. But ,if you wish to, you
  can leave this extension away.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListLoad" "List Window / Effect List / Load"

  Load a list file with the help of a file requester.

  @{u}Attention:@{uu} The program clears the complete list before it loads the selected
  list file! The file`s content replaces the current list.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListInsFile" "List Window / Effect List / Insert file"

  Insert a whole list file in front of the selected item with the help of a file
  requester. The following items are moved down appropriate.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListPrint" "List Window / Effect List / Print"

  Print the whole list.
@endnode

@node "NID_ListClear" "List Window / Effect List / Clear"

  Clear the whole list.

  @{u}Attention:@{uu} All items will be lost!
@endnode

@node "NID_ListRTDisplay" "List Window / Miscellaneous / List refresh"

  Activates the position display while processing the list. Disabling this
  function means saving a lot of work for the system.
@endnode

@node "NID_MusicWindow" "The Music Window"
@next "NID_ConfigWindow"
@prev "NID_ListWindow"

  Module players may serve as data source for the relay card via the music window.
  This way you might use e.g. an electronic relay card with the lights connected
  to it as level meter.

  @{u}You can find the following gadgets in the music window:@{uu}

  @{fg highlight}Settings@{fg text}
  @{"  Frequency   " link "NID_MusicFrequency" 0}@{"Hz" link "NID_MusicFrequencyInt" 0}
  @{"  Music source  " link "NID_MusicSource" 0}
  @{"  Music channel " link "NID_MusicChannel" 0}
  @{"  Treshold    " link "NID_MusicTreshold" 0}@{"% " link "NID_MusicTresholdInt" 0}
  @{"  Effect        " link "NID_MusicEffect" 0}
 

  @{fg highlight}Miscellaneous@{fg text}
  @{" Process         " link "NID_MusicProcess" 0}
@endnode

@node "NID_MusicFrequency" "Music Window / Settings / Frequency"
  
  Select the scanning frequency here. The current music source will
  be scanned with this frequency. A low value saves computing time
  but decreases dynamics.
@endnode

@node "NID_MusicFrequencyInt" "Music Window / Settings / Hz"
  
  Enter the scanning frequency via keyboard. Valid values reach from 1 to 99 Hz.
@endnode

@node "NID_MusicProcess" "Music Window / Miscellaneous / Process"

  This gadget starts or stops the generation of music-dependent effects.
  If checked the program opens the given @{"musik source" link "NID_MusicSource" 0} and reads
  the amplitude data of the currently played music. This data is then used
  to produce the effects.
@endnode

@node "NID_MusicSource" "Music Window / Settings / Music Source"

  This is the music source from which the music data is read.

  There are currently only two possible sources:
  A Techno-Turbo-Sound digitizer connected to the internal parallel port
  and the Hippoplayer.

@endnode

@node "NID_MusicChannel" "Music Window / Settings / Music Channel"

  You can select a specific music channel that shall be used for the effects.
  Since this is not needed for every effect this gadget is disabled in some cases.
@endnode

@node "NID_MusicTreshold" "Music Window / Settings / Threshold"

  Set a threshold in percent here needed for some effects. This gagdget will be
  disabled if the currently selected effect doesn't support a threshold.
@endnode

@node "NID_MusicTresholdInt" "Music Window / Settings / %"

  The threshold in percent.
@endnode

@node "NID_MusicEffect" "Music Window / Settings / Effect"

  Select the music effect here.
  
  Currently two effects are supported:
   - Amplitude
     The current music`s amplitude is displayed via VU-Meter.
   - Amplitude analyse
     Every ouput bit is assigned to a music channel. The output bit will be set
     if that music channel exceeds the current treshold. Otherwise it will be cleared.
   - Amplitude flasher
     If the selected music channel exceeds the current treshold
     all output bits will be set. Otherwise all bits will be cleared.
@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigWindow" "The Config Window"
@next "FENSTER"
@prev "NID_MusicWindow"

  In the config window you can load, save or reset the global settings.

  @{u}You can find the following gadgets here:@{uu}

  @{fg highlight}Options@{fg text}
  @{" Screen mode                                " link "NID_ConfigScreen" 0} @{" ? " link "NID_ConfigScreenSel" 0}
  @{" Printer                                    " link "NID_ConfigPrinter" 0} @{" ? " link "NID_ConfigPrinterSel" 0}
                                        @{" Short help " link "NID_ConfigSmallHelp" 0}
                                      @{" HF-Requester " link "NID_ConfigHFRequest" 0}
                         @{" Screenmode like Workbench " link "NID_ConfigLikeWB" 0}

  @{fg highlight}Functions{fg text}
  @{" Default all      " link "NID_ConfigDefaultAll" 0} @{" Save all      " link "NID_ConfigSaveAll" 0} @{" Load all    " link "NID_ConfigLoadAll" 0}
  @{" Default          " link "NID_ConfigDefault" 0} @{" Save          " link "NID_ConfigSave" 0} @{" Load        " link "NID_ConfigLoad" 0}
@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigScreen" "Config Window / Options / Screen mode"

  This is the currently set screen mode.
@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigScreenSel" "Config Window / Options / ScreenMode ?"

  This button opens a screen mode requester which lets you choose your prefered
  screen mode for T.U.R.D. II.
  T.U.R.D. II itself doesn't need more than 16 colors so generally a screen with 16 colors
  will work fine. However if you want to open visitor windows on T.U.R.D. II's screen
  you might want have more colors. Also the default screen size is the absolute
  minimum, a bigger screen might be better for your needs.

@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigPrinter" "Config Window / Options / Printer"

  This is the device that T.U.R.D. II uses to output data to the printer. Usually this
  is the systems' "printer.device" (which is the default).
  Obviously you cannot use a printer @{i}and@{ui} a relay card connected to the
  parallel port at the same time. So if you just have the internal one: have fun
  as human port switch.
  BTW: You shouldn't plug anything into (or out of) your Amiga while it's running!

@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigPrinterSel" "Config Window / Options / Printer ?"

  This button opens a requester that lets you choose a device used to send data
  to the printer.
@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigSmallHelp" "Config Window / Options / Short Help"

  This button enables or disabled the @{"short help" link "HILFE" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigHFRequest" "Config Window / Options / HF-Requester"

  This button enables the security requester that pops up each time you try to
  send data at a high frequency (>40 Hz) to the relays. These high frequencies
  might damage the components of your @{"relay card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0}.

  The security requester has three buttons:
  
  <Cancel>    sets the frequency to the previous value
  <Slower>    sets the frequency to 40 Hz
  <Continue>  lets you continue with the high frequency

  Be careful: NEVER disable the requester if you are using a mechanical @{"card" link "RELAISKARTEN" 0}!
@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigLikeWB" "Config Window / Options / Screenmode like Workbench"

  If this button is enabled the Workbench screenmode will be copied
  on startup instead of using its own screen mode.
@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigDefaultAll" "Config Window / Operations / Default All"

  The @{"window requester" link "NID_WinSelectWindow" 0} pops up and asks for
  which windows you would like to reset the settings.

  @{u}Be careful:@{uu} The settings for all selected window will be lost!
@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigDefault" "Config Window / Operations / Default"

  The settings of the @{"config window" link "NID_ConfigWindow" 0} will be
  reset to the defaults.
  This also resets the options availabe in this window!

  @{u}Be careful:@{uu} The current settings of the @{"config window" link "NID_ConfigWindow" 0} will be lost!

  If you also want to reset the other windows choose @{"Default all" link "NID_ConfigDefaultAll" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigSaveAll" "Config Window / Operations / Save All"

  The @{"window requester" link "NID_WinSelectWindow" 0} pops up and asks for
  which windows you would like to save the settings.
@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigSave" "Config Window / Operations / Save"

  The current settings of the @{"config window" link "NID_ConfigWindow" 0}  is saved.
  This also saves the options available in this window.

  If you also want to save the other windows choose @{"Alles sichern" link "NID_ConfigSaveAll" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigLoadAll" "Config Window / Operations / Load all"

  The @{"window requester" link "NID_WinSelectWindow" 0} pops up and asks for
  which windows you would like to load the settings.

  @{u}Be careful:@{uu} The settings for all selected window will be lost!

@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigLoad" "Config Window / Operations / Load"

  This button loads the settings of the @{"config window" link "NID_ConfigWindow" 0}.
  This also loads the options available in this window!

  @{u}Be careful:@{uu} The current settings of the @{"config window" link "NID_ConfigWindow" 0} will be lost!

  If you also want to reset the other windows choose @{"Alles laden" link "NID_ConfigLoadAll" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_WinSelectWindow" "The Window Requester"

  With this window you may choose for which windows you want to load, save or
  reset the settings. After you selected one or more windows press OK to continue
  or Cancel to abort the operation.

  @{u}The requester features these gadgets:@{uu}

  @{fg highlight}Windows@{fg text}
  @{" Port Window     " link "NID_WinSelectPort" 0}
  @{" Music Window    " link "NID_WinSelectMusi" 0}
  @{" List Window     " link "NID_WinSelectList" 0}
  @{" Schedule Window " link "NID_WinSelectTime" 0}
  @{" Random Window   " link "NID_WinSelectRand" 0}
  @{" Main Window     " link "NID_WinSelectMain" 0}
  @{" Config Window   " link "NID_WinSelectConf" 0}
  @{" This Requester  " link "NID_WinSelectWinS" 0}
@endnode

@node "NID_WinSelectPort" "Window Requester / Windows / Port Window"

  If enabled this button selects the @{"port window" link "NID_PortWindow" 0}
  as destination of the previously selected function.
@endnode

@node "NID_WinSelectMusi" "Window Requester / Windows / Music Window"

  If enabled this button selects the @{"music window" link "NID_MusicWindow" 0}
  as destination of the previously selected function.
@endnode

@node "NID_WinSelectList" "Window Requester / Windows / List Window"

  If enabled this button selects the @{"list window" link "NID_ListWindow" 0}
  as destination of the previously selected function.
@endnode

@node "NID_WinSelectTime" "Window Requester / Windows / Schedule Window"

  If enabled this button selects the @{"schedule window" link "NID_TimeWindow" 0}
  as destination of the previously selected function.
@endnode

@node "NID_WinSelectRand" "Window Requester / Windows / Random Window"

  If enabled this button selects the @{"random window" link "NID_RandomWindow" 0}
  as destination of the previously selected function.
@endnode

@node "NID_WinSelectMain" "Window Requester / Windows / Main Window"

  If enabled this button selects the @{"main window" link "NID_MainWindow" 0}
  as destination of the previously selected function.
@endnode

@node "NID_WinSelectConf" "Window Requester / Windows / Config Window"

  If enabled this button selects the @{"config window" link "NID_ConfigWindow" 0}
  as destination of the previously selected function.
@endnode

@node "NID_WinSelectWinS" "Window Requester / Windows / This Requester"

  If enabled this button selects the @{"window requester" link "NID_WinSelectWindow" 0}
  as destination of the previously selected function.
@endnode

@node "NID_SystemGadget" "System Gadgets"

  This is a system gadget. Please have a look at you OS manual for its function.
@endnode

